<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="mvp-scoping">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-planning</domain>
    <summary>Smallest product version validating a hypothesis with core problem, user, learning goal, kill criterion, Must-Have capped at 60% capacity.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>mvp</tag>
      <tag>scoping</tag>
      <tag>hypothesis</tag>
      <tag>moscow</tag>
      <tag>validation</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>MVP Scoping</title>
    <summary>Define the smallest product version that validates a hypothesis: one core problem, one user, one measurable learning goal, a kill criterion, and Must-Have features capped at 60% of build capacity. If you cannot state what you will learn and when you will stop, it is not an MVP.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Founders over-scope to cover edge cases and under-scope by accident when they mistake "minimum" for "thin." The MoSCoW + capacity guard combination forces an explicit budget split — Must ≤ 60%, Should ≤ 20%, buffer 20% — and the kill criterion prevents the MVP from becoming a permanent v1 when metrics miss. A scoped MVP is a vehicle for learning, not a feature list with a launch date. The discipline of scoping forces hard choices that clarify the core hypothesis.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting a new product or major feature where the goal is hypothesis validation, not final UX.</item>
        <item>Founder has 30+ "obvious" features and needs to cut to 3–5 buildable in one timebox without losing focus.</item>
        <item>An agent is converting an idea description into an implementation plan and needs explicit scope before SDD/spec writing.</item>
        <item>Following up with mlp-planning, micro-mvps, or product-discovery — MVP scoping is the entry gate.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Post-PMF feature work — use roadmap-design + RICE instead.</item>
        <item>Compliance-driven products where "minimum" is dictated by regulation (the floor is fixed).</item>
        <item>B2B enterprise sales where the "MVP" must include integrations and SLAs — that is an MMP, not an MVP.</item>
        <item>When you already know the answer and need to ship — skip ceremony, write the spec directly.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="framework">
      <p>What is an MVP: Minimum Viable Product is the smallest version that solves the core problem, delivers value to early adopters, and allows you to learn and iterate. The critical distinction: MVP is about learning, not about launching a polished product. Many failed startups shipped something small but never asked what they would learn from it — the result was a feature release, not an experiment. An MVP is a learning experiment wrapped in a working product.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every MVP must state a falsifiable hypothesis and a numeric kill criterion before the feature list is written.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a hypothesis, scope decisions have no anchor. Without a kill criterion, the MVP becomes a permanent v1 even when metrics miss.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Ship an MVP to validate a hypothesis; evolve to MLP (Minimum Lovable Product) only after validation.</statement>
        <rationale>MVP targets early adopters who tolerate rough edges; MLP targets retention-sensitive mainstream users. Conflating the two inflates scope before the hypothesis is proven.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>6-Step Scoping Process:</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Step 1 — Define the core problem using the template: "For [user] who [problem], our MVP proves [hypothesis] by delivering [outcome] in [timebox] with [constraints]."</statement>
        <rationale>Forces the problem statement to name a specific user, a hypothesis, and a timebox before any features appear.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Step 2 — Identify the ONE thing the product must do well; apply the value test: if you remove it, is the product useless?</statement>
        <rationale>Single core value prevents multi-axis scope — the most common cause of a 6-month MVP.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Step 3 — Brain-dump all features, then categorize each as Core, Important, Nice-to-have, or Out of Scope.</statement>
        <rationale>Separation forces explicit trade-offs before MoSCoW weighting.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Step 4 — Apply MoSCoW: Must Have ≤ 60% of capacity, Should Have ≤ 20%, reserve 20% buffer. Won't Have must be explicit and list ≥ 3 items.</statement>
        <rationale>The capacity constraint is a physical ceiling, not a guideline. Won't Have is the scope-creep firewall.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Step 5 — Validate scope against five gates: solves core problem end-to-end; first user can complete core job; value is delivered without future features; buildable in target timebox; hypothesis is testable.</statement>
        <rationale>Each gate catches a different failure mode — incompleteness, user-flow gaps, dependency holes, schedule risk, and unverifiability.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Step 6 — Define done: acceptance criteria per Must-Have feature, definition of "good enough" quality, metrics to collect, and the next decision after MVP.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a definition of done, the MVP ship date is always "almost ready."</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="examples">
      <p>Two worked examples — a time-tracking app and a course platform — showing how a 40+ feature list compresses to a 4-item Must-Have scope with explicit learning goals and kill criteria. Both examples demonstrate the discipline required to cut scope ruthlessly while preserving the core value proposition.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Time Tracking App">
        <note>Freelancers forget to track time, losing billable hours. Initial list had 40+ features. Scoped to 4-week MVP with concrete success metrics.</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
Must Have (4 weeks)       | Why
--------------------------|-----------------------------
Start/stop timer          | Core functionality
Project selection         | Assign time to project
Basic time report         | See what was tracked
Simple invoice export     | Get paid

Won't Have
- Mobile app (use responsive web)
- Team features (solo focus first)
- Integrations (manual entry for now)
- Advanced reports (spreadsheet export)

Learning goal: Will users actually track time daily?
Kill criterion: If < 30% of signups log time on 5+ days in week 2, pivot.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Course Platform">
        <note>Course creators struggle with tech setup. Scoped to 6-week MVP targeting one learning goal about market willingness to pay.</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
Must Have (6 weeks)       | Why
--------------------------|-----------------------------
Upload video/text lessons | Core content delivery
Paywall + payment         | Must monetize to test willingness-to-pay
Student access control    | Protect paid content
Basic progress tracking   | Show value to student

Won't Have
- Quizzes (manual feedback loop)
- Certificates (v2 feature)
- Community features (external Discord)
- Mobile app (responsive web)
- Advanced analytics (basic counts only)

Learning goal: Will creators pay $29/month for simplicity over feature-rich competitors?
Kill criterion: If < 5 paid subscriptions by week 8, pricing or positioning is wrong.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="Common Scope Failures">
        <note>10 Must-Have features listed for a 4-week timebox with 1 developer.</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
Must Have: auth, billing, dashboard, notifications, onboarding,
           search, reporting, settings, integrations, mobile app
Timebox: 4 weeks | Capacity: 1 dev
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="antipatterns">
      <p>Seven failure modes that produce useless or over-built MVPs, with root causes and fixes. Each pattern is recognizable in retrospect but easy to rationalize away when time pressure increases. Learn to spot them early and enforce the scope guardrails relentlessly.</p>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Must-Have list contains more than 5 features or exceeds 60% of capacity.</description>
        <reason>Every additional Must is scope creep disguised as necessity. Cap is 3–5 items; above that, re-examine whether each directly tests the hypothesis.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>MVP has no kill criterion — only a success target.</description>
        <reason>Without a kill threshold the team always finds a reason to keep going; the MVP becomes a permanent v1. Force the field: "If metric &lt; X by date Y, pivot or kill."</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>MVP takes 6+ months to build.</description>
        <reason>Six months is not an MVP — it is a product launch. Real MVPs fit inside 2–8 weeks. If the timebox is longer, the scope is wrong or the hypothesis is too broad.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Won't-Have is empty or has fewer than 3 items.</description>
        <reason>The Won't-Have list is the scope-creep firewall. An empty list means no trade-offs were made. Every MVP should explicitly exclude ≥ 3 tempting features with stated reasons.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>MVP has no learning goal — only a feature list.</description>
        <reason>Features without questions are just engineering work. The learning goal is what converts the MVP from "release" to "experiment"; if it is absent, there is nothing to learn from the launch.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Authentication and billing listed as Must-Have for v0.</description>
        <reason>Magic links replace full auth. Stripe checkout replaces in-app billing UI. Both are Should for v0 unless the hypothesis is specifically about the billing or auth experience.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>The same agent that proposes features also reviews scope.</description>
        <reason>Proposer bias inflates the Must list. Use a separate reviewer subagent that applies the 5-question quick check independently.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/mvp-scope-doc.md" purpose="Full MVP scope document with problem, feature table, learning goals, kill criterion"/>
      <template path="templates/mvp-quick-check.md" purpose="5-question validator for fast scope review"/>
      <template path="templates/mvp-capacity.py" purpose="CLI script: reads scope JSON, fails if Must-Have days exceed 60% budget or kill criterion is missing"/>
    </templates>
